At its simplest level, Locking and Unlocking are the mechanisms Java uses to ensure that only one thread can touch a specific piece of data or code at a time.
Think of a Lock as a "Physical Key" to a single-person restroom.
1. The Real-World Analogy: The Restroom
Imagine a busy office with one private restroom.
 * The Lock: There is a sign on the handle. When someone enters, they turn the deadbolt.
 * The Wait: If you arrive and the door is locked, you don't just disappear; you stand in the hallway and wait until the door opens.
 * The Unlock: When the person inside finished, they turn the deadbolt and walk out. The door is now "Available."
 * The Next Person: The first person in line grabs the handle, enters, and immediately locks it behind them.
2. The Technical Workflow
In your Java code, the process follows three strict steps:
A. The lock() (Acquisition)
When a thread calls lock.lock(), it is checking the "Door."
 * If the lock is free, the thread takes ownership and continues executing the code.
 * If the lock is held by another thread, the current thread "pauses" (blocks). It stays there until the owner releases it.
B. The "Critical Section" (The Work)
This is the code between the lock and unlock. This is where you do things that aren't safe for multiple threads, like:
 * Updating a counter++.
 * Adding an item to a List.
 * Writing to a shared file.
C. The unlock() (Release)
When the thread calls lock.unlock(), it "drops the key." This immediately notifies the threads waiting in line that the "Room" is now free.
3. Why do we need them? (The Race Condition)
If you don't use a lock, you get a Race Condition.
Imagine two threads both try to increment a variable count = 10 at the exact same time:
 * Thread A reads 10.
 * Thread B reads 10.
 * Thread A adds 1 and writes 11.
 * Thread B adds 1 and writes 11.
 * The Result: You expect 12, but you got 11 because one update was "stepped on."
By using lock() and unlock(), you force them to take turns:
 * Thread A locks, reads 10, writes 11, and unlocks.
 * Thread B was waiting. Now it locks, reads 11, writes 12, and unlocks.
4. The Golden Rule of Locking
In Java, you must always wrap your unlock in a finally block. If your code throws an error (Exception) while it has the lock, and you don't have a finally block, the lock will never be released.
> The "Restroom" would be locked forever, even though nobody is inside!
> 
lock.lock();
try {
    // Critical Section
    int result = 10 / 0; // This throws an error!
} finally {
    // This runs NO MATTER WHAT, ensuring the door is opened.
    lock.unlock(); 
}

