Yes, you absolutely can! In fact, that is exactly why it is called a ReentrantLock.
The word "Reentrant" literally means a thread can "re-enter" a lock it already owns. If Java didn't allow this, a thread would actually deadlock itself the moment it tried to call a second method that required the same lock.
How it Works: The "Hold Count"
Inside the ReentrantLock object, there is a counter.
 * When you call lock() the first time, the counter becomes 1.
 * When the same thread calls lock() again, the counter becomes 2.
 * Every time you call unlock(), the counter goes down by 1.
 * The lock is only released for other threads when the counter hits 0.
A Real-World Example: Recursive Methods
Imagine you have a method that calls itself (recursion). If you couldn't lock multiple times, the second call would hang forever.
private final ReentrantLock lock = new ReentrantLock();

public void countdown(int n) {
    lock.lock(); // Increases hold count
    try {
        System.out.println("Count: " + n + " | Hold Count: " + lock.getHoldCount());
        if (n > 0) {
            countdown(n - 1); // Recursive call re-enters the lock
        }
    } finally {
        lock.unlock(); // Decreases hold count
    }
}

If you ran countdown(3), the hold count would climb to 4, then slowly drop back to 0 as the methods finish.
The "Golden Rule" of Multiple Locking
For every lock(), there must be a matching unlock().
If you lock three times but only unlock twice, the "door" is still locked. No other thread will ever be able to enter, and your application will eventually grind to a halt.
| Action | Current State | Hold Count | Can others enter? |
|---|---|---|---|
| lock.lock() | Thread A owns it | 1 | No |
| lock.lock() | Thread A owns it | 2 | No |
| lock.unlock() | Thread A owns it | 1 | No |
| lock.unlock() | Free | 0 | Yes |
Why is this useful for your Salesforce Project?
Sometimes you might have a "Main Service" that locks a batch to process it, but that service calls a "Logging Utility" that also tries to lock the same batch to record the status.
Because of reentrancy, your code won't "trip over its own feet." It recognizes that the thread already has the key and just lets it through.
> Fun Fact: The standard synchronized keyword in Java is also reentrant! If it wasn't, almost every complex Java application would have crashed years ago.
